Hi Comfy
Reviewanon here, I said that I’d have something for you and Roo’d Awakening before morning Monday. …well what’s two business days between friends, right? First and foremost, let’s get the easy stuff out of the way. The grammar, sentence structure, and word usage are pretty well spot on. I think I saw maybe 3 major misspellings throughout the whole story, and the only real grammar issues I saw were in the characters’ dialogue. (…where they should be. Speech isn’t normally grammatically correct.) Add to this the fact that your descriptors balance nicely – not too vague, not too wordy – and it becomes apparent that you’ve got firm a grasp on your writing mechanics. Seriously. Kudos on this front.
Additionally, I have to say that your ability to create relatable, organic, likable characters is hugely commendable. Everyone from the MC to the lowly Panda at the Chinese food place has a distinct personality and speech pattern. It makes it feel like you’ve thought about their backstories, even if the reader doesn’t get to see it (don’t push more for minor characters. The balance was on point).

Another thing that I have to commend you for is story pacing. While things seem a little bit compressed timeline wise, they work well within the confines of the narrative. If I’m not mistaken, all of the actions and arcs thus far have happened within a single week, with chapter 5 wrapping up on Saturday night. Compressed or not, the arc works, the side stories are additive, and nothing about the plot or its pacing is immersion breaking.

Perhaps unsurprisingly, my critique is going to come from the same old place that most of them around here do, and that’s with the intro. If I can, I’ll try to at least provide a bit more specific input than ‘too much exposition’. In Roo’d awakening, at least, you go over a massive amount of Anon’s backstory up front that falls into the two major cardinal sins of backstory. The first of these is that the information laid out could have effectively been worked into the story ark you break into after the exposition. When you talk about Anon’s lack of long-term college friends, you could easily have revealed some of that while he was talking with Kevin. The bits about him not having many friends could have (and largely were) fed to the reader in a much more organic manner through Anon’s interactions with Kelly/Ruby/Kevin.

The 30 some lines you dedicated to Anon’s college backstory and family drinking issues run into the other major sin of exposition, which is violation of Chekhov’s gun (plot device). There’s a lot of info you’ve put in that doesn’t really need to be there to flesh out Anon’s character including the insane stuff that Anon did in college, his drinking, and his family’s issues with alcoholism. So far, these haven’t had any real relevant sway over Anon or the other characters and they haven’t come into play with any story arcs (though I realize you’re only so and so far into the story). Again, this isn’t a story breaker, and I’ve honestly really enjoyed Roo’d so far. Just some things to think about when setting up your next work, or thinking about things to tie into subsequent chapters.

Thanks again for putting this out. Looking forward to subsequent chapters!
